{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2018}} {{Infobox bus accident |title=Chattanooga school bus crash |image=File:Chattanooga, TN (31070581571).jpg |caption=[[National Transportation Safety Board|NTSB]] investigators and the damaged bus |date=November 21, 2016 |location=[[Chattanooga, Tennessee]] |bus=[[School bus]] |vehicles= |pax=35 |deaths=6 (1 later) |injuries=23 (6 critical) |}}
{{coord|35|01|27|N|85|14|05|W|scale:5000|display=title}}
In the afternoon of November 21, 2016, a [[school bus]] in [[Chattanooga]], [[Tennessee]], rolled over onto its passenger side and became wrapped around a tree. There were fatalities and injuries. The incident took place in the city's Brainerd neighborhood on Talley Road, which officials described as a "narrow, winding road". The bus, operated by [[Durham School Services]],<ref name="CNN" /> was transporting children from Woodmore Elementary School.<ref name="ABCNews">{{cite web|title=Kids Who Died in Chattanooga School Bus Crash Include 3 Fourth-Graders|url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/kids-killed-chattanooga-school-bus-crash-include-fourth/story?id=43702930|last1=Hayden|first1=Michael Edison | last2=Gallagher| first2=J.J.| last3=Liddy|first3=Tom|last4=Cook|first4=Jeffrey|website=abcnews.go.com|publisher=ABC News Internet Ventures|date=November 22, 2016|access-date=November 22, 2016}}</ref><ref name="WRCB">{{cite web|last1=Nicholson|first1=Ken|title=Driver charged in deadly Talley Road school bus crash|url=http://www.wrcbtv.com/story/33763627/update-driver-charged-in-deadly-talley-road-school-bus-crash|website=wrcbtv.com|publisher=WRCB-TV|accessdate=November 22, 2016}}</ref>
The bus was transporting 37 children. Five of the children died at the scene of the crash. 23 children were hospitalized, six of them in critical condition. A sixth child died two days later.<ref name="CNN">{{Cite web| url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/11/21/us/tennessee-chattanooga-school-bus-accident/index.html|title=6 dead in Tennessee school bus crash| last1=Sterling| first1=Joe| last2=Simon| first2=Darran| website=cnn.com| publisher=Cable News Network|date=November 21, 2016|access-date=November 22, 2016}}</ref><ref name="ABCNews" /><ref name="WBIR">{{Cite web|url=http://www.wbir.com/news/local/authorities-investigate-chattanooga-school-bus-crash/354658853|title=Bus driver charged with vehicular manslaughter in Chattanooga bus crash|last=(staff writer)|date=November 21, 2016|website=wbir.com|publisher=WBIR-TV|language=en-US|access-date=November 22, 2016}}</ref><ref name="KRQE">{{cite web|title=Drugs, alcohol not involved in bus crash; 6th child dies| url=http://krqe.com/2016/11/23/drugs-alcohol-not-involved-in-bus-crash-6th-child-dies/|website=krqe.com| publisher=LIN Television|last=Associated Press|date=November 23, 2016|access-date=November 24, 2016}}</ref>
==Investigation== The cause of the crash is under investigation, but officials believe that the speed of the bus might have been a contributing factor. On the day after the crash, a spokesman for the Chattanooga police department reported that drugs and alcohol were not factors. According to [[CBS News]] correspondent Mark Strassmann, the mother of three children on the bus, including one who died, stated that her surviving children told her that Walker asked if they were "ready to die" immediately before the crash. Chattanooga police disputed the accuracy of this claim.<ref name="KRQE" /><ref>{{cite web|title=Driver Asked Kids 'Are You Ready to Die' Before Crashing Bus in Chattanooga| url=http://detroit.cbslocal.com/2016/11/22/report-driver-asked-kids-are-you-ready-to-die-before-crashing-bus-in-chattanooga/|website=detroit.cbslocal.com|publisher=CBS Local Media|last=(staff writer)|date=November 22, 2016|access-date=November 23, 2016}}</ref>
Chattanooga Officers testified during the 2016 hearing that the school bus traveled between 48 and 52 mph, in a 30 mph zone. Students had previously complained about Walker's quality of driving and the private company that he was employed under, Durham School Services, had a history of traffic accidents in Tennessee.<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=https://www.tennessean.com/story/news/local/2018/02/26/chattanooga-school-bus-crash-what-know-trial-gets-underway/374499002/|title=Deadly Chattanooga school bus crash: What to know as trial gets underway|work=The Tennessean|access-date=2018-04-19|language=en}}</ref>
==Legal proceedings== [[File:Chattanooga School Bus Crash Press Conference (31184885515).jpg|thumb|NTSB briefing]] Johnthony K. Walker, the driver, was arrested and charged with six counts of vehicular homicide, reckless endangerment, and reckless driving.<ref name="ABCNews" /><ref name="WBIR" /> On March 1, 2018, Walker was convicted of six counts of criminally negligent homicide, 11 counts of reckless aggravated assault, seven counts of assault, reckless endangerment, reckless driving and using his phone.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wbir.com/article/news/crime/bus-driver-found-guilty-of-criminally-negligent-homicide-in-crash-that-killed-6-kids/51-524203588|title=Bus driver found guilty of criminally negligent homicide in crash that killed 6 kids|work=wbir.com|access-date=2018-06-16|language=en-US}}</ref> In addition a Hamilton County Criminal Court jury convicted Walker of lesser charges for the crash. He was sentenced to four years in prison, but went free on bail pending an appeal. In June 2018, while still free on bail pending an appeal of the bus crash charges, Walker was arrested for raping a 14-year-old girl at a home where he was staying.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tennessean.com/story/news/crime/2018/06/14/driver-2016-chattanooga-bus-crash-charged-rape-nashville/704263002/ |title=Johnthony K. Walker, driver in fatal Chattanooga bus crash, charged in rape in Nashville |work= |author= |date= |accessdate=June 16, 2018}}</ref>
