[[File:SealofWestBoylstonMA.png|thumb|right|The Beaman Oak is within the seal of West Boylston]] The '''Beaman Oak''' was the largest [[white oak]] tree in the Commonwealth of [[Massachusetts]]. It stood in the front yard of a [[Colonial history of the United States|colonial era]] three-story house in the town of [[Lancaster, Massachusetts|Lancaster]]. It was so named because Gamaliel Beaman had originally settled the spot in 1659. The oak became known as a prominent landmark in Central Massachusetts and is featured prominently on the town seal of [[West Boylston, Massachusetts|West Boylston]].
In 1970, the Beaman Oak's circumference at its base was {{convert|31|ft|abbr=on}}, with a circumference {{convert|5|ft|abbr=on}} above the base of {{convert|31|ft|abbr=on}}, and its height was {{convert|75|ft|abbr=on}} and spread was {{convert|75|ft|abbr=on}}.
The oak's trunk was partially hollow towards the end of its life. After a storm severely damaged it, the tree was cut down in 1989.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.ci.lancaster.ma.us/Pages/LancasterMA_CommDev/PLAN_HISTORIC_PRES_ELEMENT_VI.pdf |title= Lancaster, Massachusetts Historic Preservation Plan |accessdate=2010-11-01 |date= 2007| deadurl=yes |publisher= Town of Lancaster, Massachusetts| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927032352/http://www.ci.lancaster.ma.us/Pages/LancasterMA_CommDev/PLAN_HISTORIC_PRES_ELEMENT_VI.pdf |archivedate=2011-09-27 |df= }}</ref>
