{{Infobox theatre | name = Valentine Theatre | image = ValentineTheatre.jpg | image_size = 250px | image_alt = | caption = | image_map = | map_caption = | pushpin_map = | pushpin_map_caption= | address = 410 Adams Street | city = [[Toledo, Ohio]] | country = [[United States]] | designation = | coordinates = {{Coord|41.6528|N|83.5342|W|region:US-OH_type:landmark|display=inline,title}} | architect = [[E.O. Fallis]] | owner = Toledo Cultural Arts Center | tenant = | operator = [[Columbus Association for the Performing Arts|CAPA]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.broadwayworld.com/cleveland/article/CAPA-Set-To-Manage-Toledos-Valentine-Theatre-20090622|title=CAPA Set To Manage Toledo's Valentine Theatre|first=BWW News|last=Desk|publisher=|accessdate=24 October 2016}}</ref> | capacity = 901 | type = | opened = {{Start date|1895|12|25}} | reopened = October 9, 1999 | yearsactive = | rebuilt = | closed = | demolished = | othernames = | production = | currentuse = | website = {{URL|http://www.valentinetheatre.com}} }}
The '''Valentine Theatre''' is located in the [[Downtown Toledo|downtown]] district of [[Toledo, Ohio]] at the corner of Superior and Adams Streets. The {{Age|1895|12|25}}-year-old facility seats 901. It is owned by the Toledo Cultural Arts Center and operated by the [[Columbus Association for the Performing Arts]].
The building was added to the [[National Register of Historic Places]] on May 19, 1987.<ref name="nris">{{NRISref|version=2009a}}</ref> A $28 million renovation of the building carried out by architect Charles H. Stark, begun in 1978 and taking 21 years to complete, was unveiled on October 9, 1999.<ref name="valentine">{{cite web|url=http://www.valentinetheatre.com/about.html|title=The Valentine Theatre|first=|last=Administrator|publisher=|accessdate=24 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.americantowns.com/oh/toledo/organization/valentine_theatre|title=Valentine Theatre - Toledo, OH|publisher=|accessdate=24 October 2016}}</ref>
On November 23, 2007, a natural gas explosion in the basement caused extensive damage and forced the evacuation of the adjoining Renaissance Senior Apartments.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Weber|first1=Laren|title=Valentine 'safe' after blast; damage appears cosmetic|url=http://www.toledoblade.com/Police-Fire/2007/11/24/Valentine-safe-after-blast-damage-appears-cosmetic.html|website=Toledo Blade|accessdate=5 February 2018}}</ref> The theater reopened in April 2008 after repairs costing $3.5 million.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Reindl|first1=JC|title=Renaissance residents return to downtown Toledo apartments|url=http://www.toledoblade.com/local/2008/05/28/Renaissance-residents-return-to-downtown-Toledo-apartments.html|website=Toledo Blade|accessdate=5 February 2018}}</ref>
